               <p>
               <mixed-citation id="d71e204" publication-type="book">
Anderson and Eisenmenger rely on Grebler
[10]  </mixed-citation>
            </p>
               <p>
               <mixed-citation id="d71e215" publication-type="unknown">
Fisher and Siegman [8]</mixed-citation>
            </p>
               <p>
               <mixed-citation id="d71e221" publication-type="unknown">
Fisher and Siegman in turn rely on Grebler, the
latter's comments are instructive: "Proponents of the plan refer to its long-standing general
acceptance in Great Britain where the building societies dominate the home mortgage market
and customarily have written mortgages with 'interest variation' clauses, and to similar ex-
perience in other countries. To judge from responses to our questionnaires, however, it seems
that the variable-rate mortgage is not as common on the European continent as in Great
Britain.... The variable-rate mortgage is used only by the depository-type institutions, and
only in some European countries" (pp. 78-79).</mixed-citation>
            </p>
               <p>
               <mixed-citation id="d71e250" publication-type="journal">
Anderson and
Eisenmenger, following Fisher and Siegman, say variable rates are in widespread use, he writes,
"Savings banks use the variable rate clause, but not often, and can invoke the clause in most
cases only five years after the mortgage loan was originated" (p. 125).  <fpage>125</fpage>
               </mixed-citation>
            </p>
            </fn>
